Actually, looking at the code more carefully:
```csharp
.ConfigureHttpMessageHandlerBuilder(b =>
{
    ((HttpClientHandler)b.PrimaryHandler).UseCookies = false;
});
```

The method `ConfigureHttpMessageHandlerBuilder` was marked obsolete in .NET 8 and the recommended replacement is `ConfigurePrimaryHttpMessageHandler`. 

But there's a bigger problem: in .NET 9, the default primary handler changed to `SocketsHttpHandler`, so that cast to `HttpClientHandler` will fail at runtime. I need to identify all the breaking changes affecting this migration. The main ones are the target framework change from `net8.0` to `net9.0`, and the HttpClientFactory now using `SocketsHttpHandler` by default instead of `HttpClientHandler`, which means the cast will throw an `InvalidCastException`. The fix would involve using `UseSocketsHttpHandler` or switching to `ConfigurePrimaryHttpMessageHandler` with the appropriate handler type.

